<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,949,1535]" pageId="1" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,289,949,975]" pageId="1" pageNumber="17">Diagnoses.</emphasis>
The genus was adequately characterized by 
<bibRefCitation author="Lugo-Ortiz, C. R. &amp; McCafferty, W. P." box="[846,1279,949,975]" pageId="1" pageNumber="17" pagination="156 - 169" refId="ref6916" refString="Lugo-Ortiz, C. R. &amp; McCafferty, W. P. (1996) Taxonomy of the Neotropical Genus Americabaetis, New Status (Insecta: Ephemeroptera: Baetidae). Studies on Neotropical Fauna and Environment, 31, 156 - 169." type="journal article" year="1996">Lugo-Ortiz and McCafferty (1996)</bibRefCitation>
and later by 
<bibRefCitation author="Dominguez, E. &amp; Molineri, C. &amp; Pescador, M. L. &amp; Hubbard, M. D. &amp; Nieto, C." box="[151,443,986,1012]" pageId="1" pageNumber="17" pagination="646" refId="ref6608" refString="Dominguez, E., Molineri, C., Pescador, M. L., Hubbard, M. D. &amp; Nieto, C. (2006) Ephemeroptera of South America. In: Adis, J., Arias, J. R., Rueda-Delgado, G. &amp; Wantzen, K. M. (Eds), Aquatic Biodiversity of Latin America. Vol. 2. Pensoft, Moscow-Sofia, p. 646." type="book chapter" year="2006">
Domínguez 
<emphasis box="[295,346,986,1011]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="17">et al</emphasis>
. (2006)
</bibRefCitation>
. Herein we add one important character regarding the nymphal stage which has been observed in all Brazilian species as well as in an unidentified species from Central America: the shape of the lateral branch of the epicranial suture. In most baetids they are straight or curved, while in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lugo-Ortiz &amp; McCafferty" authorityYear="1996" box="[1209,1378,1061,1086]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Americabaetis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1209,1378,1061,1086]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="17">Americabaetis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
they are sinuous, somewhat similar to those of the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Needham &amp; Murphy" authorityName="Needham &amp; Murphy" authorityYear="1924" box="[782,1151,1098,1124]" class="Insecta" family="Baetidae" genus="Baetodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[782,891,1099,1124]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="17">Baetodes</emphasis>
Needham &amp; Murphy
</taxonomicName>
, and can be very useful when identifying nymphs of the family (see 
<figureCitation box="[680,763,1136,1162]" captionStart="FIGURES 2–8" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1898,1922]" captionTargetBox="[223,1364,209,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-70@3.[204,1382,194,1877]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 2–8. Americabaetis mecistognathus, sp. nov. Nymph. 2. Head (f.v.); 3. Labrum (left d.v., right v.v.); 4a. Left mandible (d.v.); 4b. Left mandible, detail of incisors and prostheca; 5a. Right mandible (d.v.); 5b. Right mandible, detail of incisors and prostheca. 6. Hypopharynx (d.v.); 7. Maxilla (v.v.); 8. Labium (left d.v, right v.v.)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302611/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="17">Figs. 2</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[777,898,1136,1162]" captionStart="FIGURES 18–26" captionStartId="9.[151,270,1195,1219]" captionTargetBox="[183,1405,203,1164]" captionTargetId="figure-293@9.[174,1413,194,1174]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 18–26. Americabaetis spp. Nymph. 18. Head of A. labiosus (frontal view); 19. Head of A. longetron (f.v.); 20. Labial palp of A. alphus; 21. Labial palp of A. labiosus; 22. Abdomen in dorsal view of A. longetron; 23. Abdomen in dorsal view of A. alphus (male); 24. Abdomen in dorsal view of A. alphus (female); 25. Posterior margin of terga IV of A. labiosus; 26. Posterior margin of terga IV of A. longetron." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5302617" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5302617/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="17">18 and 19</figureCitation>
). Other characteristic that can be emended to the nymphal diagnoses is the presence of scales and/or scale bases over body.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="17" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,949,1535]" pageId="1" pageNumber="17">
Nymphs (modified from 
<bibRefCitation author="Dominguez, E. &amp; Molineri, C. &amp; Pescador, M. L. &amp; Hubbard, M. D. &amp; Nieto, C." box="[509,801,1210,1236]" pageId="1" pageNumber="17" pagination="646" refId="ref6608" refString="Dominguez, E., Molineri, C., Pescador, M. L., Hubbard, M. D. &amp; Nieto, C. (2006) Ephemeroptera of South America. In: Adis, J., Arias, J. R., Rueda-Delgado, G. &amp; Wantzen, K. M. (Eds), Aquatic Biodiversity of Latin America. Vol. 2. Pensoft, Moscow-Sofia, p. 646." type="book chapter" year="2006">
Domínguez 
<emphasis box="[661,715,1211,1236]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="17">et al</emphasis>
. 2006
</bibRefCitation>
): 1) Lateral branch of epicranial suture sinuous; 2) mandibles with setae between prostheca and mola, incisors fused apically, and prostheca robust with denticles apically; 3) maxillary palp two-segmented; 4) glossa with a row of long spine-like setae, paraglossae rectangular with 3 rows of long spine-like setae, segment II of labial palp with a distomedial projection; 5) tarsal claws with a single row of denticles; 6) hind wing pads absent; 7) abdominal gills present on segment II–VII; 8) scales and/or scale bases over body.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,949,1535]" pageId="1" pageNumber="17">
Male imagos (modified from 
<bibRefCitation author="Dominguez, E. &amp; Molineri, C. &amp; Pescador, M. L. &amp; Hubbard, M. D. &amp; Nieto, C." box="[551,830,1434,1460]" pageId="1" pageNumber="17" pagination="646" refId="ref6608" refString="Dominguez, E., Molineri, C., Pescador, M. L., Hubbard, M. D. &amp; Nieto, C. (2006) Ephemeroptera of South America. In: Adis, J., Arias, J. R., Rueda-Delgado, G. &amp; Wantzen, K. M. (Eds), Aquatic Biodiversity of Latin America. Vol. 2. Pensoft, Moscow-Sofia, p. 646." type="book chapter" year="2006">
Domínguez 
<emphasis box="[697,750,1435,1460]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="17">et al</emphasis>
. 2006
</bibRefCitation>
): 1) Dorsal portion of turbinate eyes ellipsoidal; 2) forewings with paired (seldom single) marginal intercalary veins; 3) hind wings absent; 4) genitalia with forceps three-segmented, segment III elongate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
